<HEADLINE>
<P>
THEATER REVIEW; 'MURDER ON NILE' COASTS ON CONVERSATION; WESTMINSTER 
COMMUNITY'S WELL-DRESSED CAST MAKES THE TALK WORK IN AGATHA CHRISTIE'S 
CHARACTER PLAY, BUT THE PRODUCTION IS BARREN. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By M.E. WARREN, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 "Murder on the Nile" follows many of the formulas that have made its author, 
Dame Agatha Christie, the traditional queen of murder mysteries. Isolate an 
eccentric collection of humanity from the world, kill one of them and give 
everyone else a motive for murder. 
</P>
<P>
 In Christie's most popular plays, "Ten Little Indians" and "The Mousetrap," 
she gives us not one victim, but a whole series of them. The characters are 
murdered one after another, and it is a matter of survival to discover the 
killer. 
</P>
<P>
 "Murder on the Nile" is a rather different stage animal. It's a play about the 
characters rather than the crime. There is a murder, of course, but more than 
anything else, there is a great deal of talk. 
</P>
<P>
 The Westminster Community Theatre production of "Murder on the Nile" is 
modestly successful at making the talk interesting, thanks largely to a cast 
that is clear-spoken and well-dressed in designer June Steneck's classy 
black-and-white costumes.  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Steneck's costumes definitely suggest the '40s, but the black-and-white 
production design backfires with the set, which is visually and dramatically 
barren. The story is set on the observation deck of a paddle steamer going down 
the Nile, but the heat and the scenery are only talk: The production never 
leaves Orange County. 
</P>
<P>
 Director Marc LeBlanc's staging is arid enough. There's nothing to do on this 
observation deck except to talk. Consequently, movement is awkward, motivated 
by sight lines rather than action. Even the drinks are brought in from offstage 
by the steward (played by Bill Meadows in the one performance that is touched 
with a sense of humor). 
</P>
<P>
 The net result is a rather sleepy evening, roused by a few gunshots. The real 
firepower of the play, waiting to be triggered into blazing looks and deadly 
innuendo, is still lurking, undetected, in all that talk. 
</P>
<P>
 * "Murder on the Nile," Westminster Community Theatre, 7272 Maple St., 
Westminster. Friday and Saturday, 8:30 p.m.; matinee Jan. 30, 2 p.m. Ends Feb. 
5. $7 to $9. (714) 527-8463. Running time: 2 hours, 15 minutes. Bill Meadows 
Steward 
</P>
<P>
 Renee Oran: Miss ffoliot-ffoulkes 
</P>
<P>
 Claudia Ehrhardt: Christina Grant 
</P>
<P>
 Edwin D. Schuyler: Smith 
</P>
<P>
 Susan Meylor: Louise 
</P>
<P>
 Bob Goff: Dr. Bressner 
</P>
<P>
 Alison Boole: Kay Mostyn 
</P>
<P>
 Philip Lance: Simon Mostyn 
</P>
<P>
 Edward J. Steneck: Canon Pennefather 
</P>
<P>
 Lisa Harvey: Jacqueline de Severac 
</P>
<P>
 A Westminster Community Theatre production of the Agatha Christie mystery. 
Produced by Sandi Newcomb and Edward J. Steneck. Directed by Marc LeBlanc. 
Costumes: June Steneck. 
</P>
</TEXT>
