<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFF THE TICKER: GOOD HEALTH HAS ITS LIMITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Americans are supposedly more conscious of their fat and calorie intake, but 
it would seem they don't give a hoot when it comes to ice cream. 
</P>
<P>
 The International Ice Cream Assn. says sales of higher-fat, super-premium ice 
creams rose 8% in 1992, while sales of lower-fat, cheaper ice creams were 
unchanged to slightly lower. 
</P>
<P>
 A Penn State food scientist, Dr. Arun Kilara, says consumers figure they're 
treating themselves so "why not go all the way." 
</P>
</TEXT>
