<HEADLINE>
<P>
BOYS' BASKETBALL ROUNDUP; A FREEWAY LEAGUE VICTORY, REVENGE IS SWEET FOR TROY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS FOSTER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A mere two games into Freeway League play and Troy's basketball team already 
is celebrating victories with group hugs at midcourt. 
</P>
<P>
 But Coach T.J. Hardeman was not about to spoil the Warriors' good time. Not 
after their 59-55 overtime victory over Sonora Wednesday night at Sonora. 
</P>
<P>
 It ended the Raiders' 13-game league winning streak and also made the Warriors 
the league's front-runner. It also avenged a 26-point loss to the Raiders in a 
tournament this season. 
</P>
<P>
 "There were some rumblings that Sonora was going to go undefeated again," 
Hardeman said. "It's not going to happen now." 
</P>
<P>
 Troy (11-7, 2-0) made sure by outscoring the Raiders, 5-1, in overtime. Sonora 
didn't exactly help itself by going zero for five from the field in the extra 
period. 
</P>
<P>
 Jeff Sand's free throw finally clinched the victory with two seconds left. 
</P>
<P>
 By outlasting the Raiders, Troy was saved from a devastating loss. The 
Warriors (11-7, 2-0) controlled the game for nearly three quarters only to 
nearly hand it to Sonora. 
</P>
<P>
 The Raiders appeared tentative when Troy went to a zone defense in the first 
quarter. It neutralized Craig Clark, Sonora's 7-foot center, who had scored 
seven points in the first two minutes. He scored only seven more the rest of 
the game. 
</P>
<P>
 Troy built a 12-point lead with outside shooting, including eight three-point 
field goals. Greg Abbott's three-point play gave Troy a 47-35 lead with 2 
minutes 40 seconds left. 
</P>
<P>
 But the Warriors hit a cold spell, making only three of 17 field-goal attempts 
during the final 10 minutes 40 seconds of the game. 
</P>
<P>
 Sonora (14-4, 1-1) nearly won the game at the end of regulation, but Chad 
Fister's three-point field goal came a second after the buzzer. 
</P>
<P>
 "We now know this is going to be a tough league," Sonora Coach Mike Murphy 
said. "So maybe this is good for us." CHRIS FOSTER 
</P>
</TEXT>
