<P>
PRO FOOTBALL DAILY REPORT; AROUND THE NFL; PACKERS IGNORING ODDS AGAINST THEM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Coach Mike Holmgren knows the line, and he wants to make sure his Green Bay 
Packers know it too. 
</P>
<P>
 The Dallas Cowboys are 14-point favorites over the Packers for Sunday's NFC 
divisional playoff at Texas Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
 "That's a lot in this league," Holmgren said. "They (players) look at those 
things. They're human. It conjures up some emotion." 
</P>
<P>
 "We don't buy that 13-point underdog thing," defensive back Terrell Buckley 
said. "Half the time, they (oddsmakers) are not right." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Author Tom Clancy is heading a partnership interested in buying the New 
England Patriots and moving the team to Hartford, a Connecticut official said 
Wednesday night. The Connecticut Development Authority agreed after a daylong 
meeting to back up with state bonds a bid by Clancy's group to purchase the NFL 
franchise, CDA president and executive director John J.C. Herndon said. . . . 
Ron Lynn resigned as defensive coordinator of the Cincinnati Bengals. 
