<HEADLINE>
<P>
CLAIRE MCNAIR DIES; RITES TO BE FRIDAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Claire MacDonald McNair, former president of the Children's Home Society and 
board member of the Orange County Mental Health Assn. and other groups, died 
Tuesday. She was 69. 
</P>
<P>
 Memorial services will be held at Chapman University Chapel in Orange at 11:30 
a.m. Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 A resident of Orange County for 30 years, Mrs. McNair was president of Chapman 
University's Town and Gown Society. She was also a founder of a group that has 
held fund-raising auctions for Western Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
 She also was board chairman of the local Multiple Sclerosis Society and a 
founding member of the associates for the advancement of nursing science and 
research for UCI Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
 "She's always been an inspiration," said her daughter, Cheri Ball. "She was 
always positive and always cared about people. She was always giving of 
herself. She was a very loving lady. In the 30 years that she's been in Orange, 
she just never stopped giving. And she always had time for her family." 
</P>
<P>
 Mrs. McNair owned a dress shop in Tustin. 
</P>
<P>
 She is survived by a son, Joel of Virginia; two sisters, Peggy Wright of 
Mission Viejo and Leslie Wilson of Tustin, and a brother, Clifford McDonald of 
Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
 In lieu of flowers, donations may be made to the Orange County Chapter of the 
Multiple Sclerosis Society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Obituary 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA011394-0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 003629 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
January 13, 1994, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 1; Column 2; Sports Desk 
</P>
